The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, March 11, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, March 10: Vijay Kelkar, adviser to the Union finance minister, has been entrusted with the new task of preparing the quarterly review of the economy as mandated under the Fiscal Responsibility and Budget Management Act. He will head the panel set up for this purpose. Other panel members include finance secretary D. C. Gupta, revenue secretary Vineeta Rai, budget secretary D. Swarup and banking secretary N. S. Sisodia. 																								 Mumbai, March 10: The Reserve Bank of India has directed banks to waive electronic clearing system (ECS) charges for income tax refund orders as and when the ECS mode is adopted by the government for refund of taxes.																								 New Delhi, March 10: The Telecom Regulatory Authority of India (Trai) today virtually gave an ultimatum to VSNL to provide bandwidth to ILD operators that will give them access to landing facilities, failing which the regulator will intervene.																								 New Delhi, March 10: Apollo Tyres has completed the preferential allotment of shares to Michelin. In November last, the Apollo board had agreed to Michelins purchase of 14.9 per cent equity through a preferential allotment for about Rs 129 crore to set up a joint venture, Michelin Apollo Tyres.																								 Calcutta, March 10: Jessop and Co Ltd has reported a net profit of Rs 29 lakh in the third quarter ended December, 2003, against a net loss of Rs 12.70 crore in the corresponding previous quarter.
